    <title type="html"><![CDATA[Changing Keybinds in vifm]]></title>
    <link href="http://jasonwryan.github.com/blog/2009/12/28/changing-keybinds-in-vifm/"/>
    <updated>2009-12-28T13:50:00+13:00</updated>
    <id>http://jasonwryan.github.com/blog/2009/12/28/changing-keybinds-in-vifm</id>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p><a href="http://vifm.sourceforge.net/">Vifm</a> is a ncurses based file manager with vi-like
keybindings; it gives you complete keyboard control over your files without
having to learn a new set of commands.</p>

<p><a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/jasonwryan/4220632362/" title="Vifm by
jasonwryan, on Flickr" target="_blank"><img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4039/4220632362_ea980811e1.jpg" width="500"
height="227" alt="Vifm"/></a></p>

<p>The only drawback, for me, is that as of the current version (0.5-1) you
can't map keys. While the developer has indicated it is on the todo list,
he also flagged that it is some way off. If, like me, you <code>map : ;</code>
in <a href="http://www.vim.org/">Vim</a>, then not having this functionality is a minor
irritant. Fortunately, it is also easily fixed. Ken Steen, the Vifm developer,
was kind enough to point me in the right direction…</p>

<p>Download <a href="http://aur.archlinux.org/packages.php?ID=6011">the tarball</a> from
<acronym title="Arch User Repository">AUR</acronym> and untar it etc.,</p>

<p><div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'> <div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>tar -xzf vifm.tar.gz <span class="nb">cd </span>vifm/
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></notextile></div></p>

<p>Build the package</p>

<p><div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'> <div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>makepkg -s
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></notextile></div></p>

<p>Then you will need to edit the file, keys.c</p>

<p><div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'> <div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'>vim src/vifm-0.5/src/keys.c
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></notextile></div></p>

<p>Search for the command key</p>

<p><div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'> <div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'>/case <span class="s1">&#39;:&#39;</span>:
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></notextile></div></p>

<p>In this version it is at line 982. Change the entry to your key of choice —
in my case <kbd>;</kbd> — and save and quit.</p>

<p>Recompile Vifm and you are done&#8230;</p>

<p><div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'> <div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='sh'><span class='line'><span class="nv">$ </span>makepkg -efi
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></notextile></div></p>

<h3>Update 18/2/10</h3>

<p>Vifm has now been moved to Community, so you can use
<a href="http://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Arch_Build_System%22">ABS</a> to build the package.</p>
]]></content>
